    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2020-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2020-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">Activity Result 4: Capacity of the Disaster Management Team members and the National Disaster Centre to prepare and respond to disasters enhanced. 
Targets:
1. 1xDMT Annual Terms of Reference, Work Plan and Compact on accountability in place.
2. 1xAROB preparedness to respond to disasters and emergencies is improved.
3. 1xDisaster Management Team is prepared to respond to multi - hazard sudden - and - slow - onset events and crisis.
4. 1xTechnical inputs to DIsater Management Act have been incorporated.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. DMT annual terms of reference, annual work plan and compact on accountability endorsed at 28 February meeting
2. 15 DMT meetings (6 ad hoc, 7 regular, 1 donor briefing, 1 CERF refresher workshop)
3. 6 ICCG meetings (2 for refugee emergency response, 2 for COVID-19 planning, 2 for La Ni&#xF1;a planning)
4. Monitored/reported more than 30 disaster events, including La Ni&#xF1;a, African Swine Fever, Fall Army Worm infestation, 
  hydrometeorological events, seismic events, and conflicts
5. Facilitated the monitoring/transition of the refugee emergency response plan
6. Coordinated the production, revision and monitoring of the DMT COVID-19 multi-sector response plan, including financial 
  tracking and 4Ws.
7. The ICCG reviewed and updated the slow- and sudden-onset plans, including in-country staffing and resources and 
  surge capacity, to draft a La Ni&#xF1;a contingency plan
8. Facilitated a review of the 1984 Disaster Management Act with Government, non-governmental and faith-based 
  organizations, key donors and the Red Cross Movement.
9. 11 communities have successfully constructed water harvesting systems. 3 communities have received training on Covid- 
  19 and capacity-building activities on water, sanitation and hygiene management, and 9 communities received training on 
  maintenance of the water catchment systems.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2019-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2019-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. 1 draft NDRRF Action Plan
2. 1 draft Monitoring &amp; Reporting Tool for NDRRF
3. 1 DRM Capacity Needs Assessment and Capacity Development Plan
4. 1 Resourcing Plan for NDC 
5. 1 Disaster Loss Database (including records for at least 5 Provinces)
6. 5 Provincial DM offices equipped
7. 5 Final MHRA and Risk Reduction Plans
8. 2 Provincial Implementation plans for NDRRF in draft
9. 1 Provincial or District Development Plan with DRR elements
10. 1 Government Submission (National Recovery Framework)
11. 1 approved provincial recovery plan
12. 1 El Nino Early Action Plan
13. 5 DMT Meetings
14. 50% of resources mobilized for EAP
15. 1 operational inter-cluster group meeting
16. 1 rapid assessment tool training package
17. 2 assessment training sessions
18. 1 assessment report produced
19. 1 draft plan on engaging private sector in DM</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">Apart from achieving all set targets, through this Project, UNDP&#x2019;s investment in disaster preparedness saw the development of three national plans. These plans have been developed with the National Disaster Centre, selected Provincial Governments and members of the national Disaster Management Team. These plans will address respectively a: slow onset (El Ni&#xF1;o) event; mid-scale multi-hazard sudden onset event; and a conflict/civil unrest event. that address how the international humanitarian actors in PNG will support the government to respond to sudden and slow-onset natural hazards, as well as a conflict/civil unrest scenario in Bougainville and a refugee emergency along the border with Indonesia. With these plans, regardless of the hazard that causes the emergency, the immediate impacts are predictable and, therefore, the response for these can be planned.

PNG&#x2019;s Disaster Management Team (DMT) is the coordination body for international humanitarian assistance. With the UNDP&#x2019;s support and through the Project, the DMT is now better prepared to quickly and effectively coordinate international humanitarian assistance for a variety of natural disasters and human-induced crises that are likely to occur in the country over the next year. The Government knows what it can expect from international humanitarian partners when the next disaster occurs, and how it will coordinate with DMT members and partners. Development partners/donors are confident that the international humanitarian community are prepared to effectively coordinate humanitarian assistance in support of Government and national partners.

Early warning measures planned under the stewardship of the National Disaster Centre and the Ntional Weather Service have been slowed by similar changes in leadership in this institution. Matters are complicated Government&#x2019;s continuing budget pressures which have affected recurrent budgetary flows across a range of departments.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
